Understanding the Problem

Objective:

Build and evaluate deep learning models capable of accurately classifying images of dogs and cats. The goal is to explore both a custom neural network and a transfer learning approach (VGG16) to identify which performs better in terms of accuracy, precision, recall, and generalization. This can be extended to other animal image classification tasks and is foundational for real-world image recognition systems.

Approach:

We will work with a subset of the Dogs vs Cats dataset consisting of 5,000 labeled images. The project will include:

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Analyze the dataset through visualizations and statistics to understand the distribution and characteristics of the image data.

Model Training

Model 1: Train a custom Convolutional Neural Network (CNN).

Model 2: Fine-tune a VGG16 model pre-trained on ImageNet using transfer learning.

Model Evaluation Compare model performance using:

Accuracy

Confusion matrix

Precision, recall, F1-score

Precision-recall curve

# Set base path and number of images to use
data_dir = "data/train"
NUM_IMAGES = 5000  # we can change this later to use more or fewer images
 
# List and filter image files
all_filenames = os.listdir(data_dir)
image_files = [f for f in all_filenames if f.lower().endswith(('.jpg', '.jpeg', '.png'))]
random.seed(42)
random.shuffle(image_files)
image_files = image_files[:NUM_IMAGES]

# Create DataFrame and assign labels
df = pd.DataFrame(image_files, columns=['filename'])
df['label'] = df['filename'].apply(lambda x: 1 if 'dog' in x.lower() else 0)
df = df.sample(frac=1, random_state=42).reset_index(drop=True)

print("Image data loaded and labeled.")
print(f"Total image files used: {len(df)}")
print(df['label'].value_counts())
print(df.head())

6. Build and Train Vanilla CNN ( Model 1)

In[7]:
cnn_model = models.Sequential([
    layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(150, 150, 3)),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(2, 2),
    layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(2, 2),
    layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(2, 2),
    layers.Flatten(),
    layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dropout(0.5),
    layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

# Compile the model
cnn_model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Callbacks for saving the best model and early stopping
cnn_checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(
    "model/best_cnn_model.h5",  #  Save in HDF5 format inside 'model' folder
    save_best_only=True,
    monitor='val_loss',
    mode='min'
)


# Early stopping to prevent overfitting
cnn_early_stop = EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_loss', 
    patience=3, 
    restore_best_weights=True)

# Train the CNN model
history = cnn_model.fit(
    X_train, y_train,
    epochs=10,
    batch_size=32,
    validation_data=(X_val, y_val),
    callbacks=[cnn_checkpoint, cnn_early_stop]
)
# ####
# The Training will stop early if the validation loss does not improve for 3 consecutive epochs.
# #####

10. Transfer Learning with VGG16

In[]:
X_train_vgg = preprocess_input(X_train.copy() * 255.0)
X_val_vgg = preprocess_input(X_val.copy() * 255.0)

base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(150, 150, 3))
for layer in base_model.layers:
    layer.trainable = False
for layer in base_model.layers[-4:]:
    layer.trainable = True

inputs = Input(shape=(150, 150, 3))
x = base_model(inputs, training=False)
x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
x = layers.Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

fine_tune_model = models.Model(inputs, outputs)

fine_tune_model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-5), loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

vgg_checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(
    "model/best_vgg_model.h5", 
    save_best_only=True, 
    monitor='val_loss', 
    mode='min')

early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3, restore_best_weights=True)

history_finetune = fine_tune_model.fit(
    X_train_vgg, y_train,
    validation_data=(X_val_vgg, y_val),
    epochs=10,
    batch_size=32,
    callbacks=[early_stop, vgg_checkpoint]
)

def evaluate_model(name, y_true, y_pred, y_probs):
    print(f"### {name} Evaluation ###")
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred):.4f}")
    print("Confusion Matrix:")
    print(confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred))
    print("Classification Report:")
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=['Cat', 'Dog']))

evaluate_model("Vanilla CNN", y_val, cnn_labels, cnn_preds)
evaluate_model("VGG16", y_val, vgg_labels, vgg_preds)

3- Plot Precision-Recall Curve

In[16]:
def plot_pr_curve(y_true, y_probs, label):
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_probs)
    avg_precision = average_precision_score(y_true, y_probs)
    plt.plot(recall, precision, label=f"{label} (AP={avg_precision:.2f})")

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plot_pr_curve(y_val, cnn_preds, "Vanilla CNN")

plt.ylabel("Precision")
plt.title("Precision-Recall Curve")

4- Show Misclassified Examples

In[17]:
def show_misclassified(X_val, y_true, y_pred, model_name):
    misclassified = np.where(y_true != y_pred.reshape(-1))[0]
    print(f"{model_name} - Total Misclassified: {len(misclassified)}")
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    for i, idx in enumerate(misclassified[:5]):
        plt.subplot(1, 5, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(X_val[idx])
        plt.title(f"True: {'Dog' if y_true[idx] else 'Cat'}\nPred: {'Dog' if y_pred[idx] else 'Cat'}")
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.suptitle(f"{model_name} - Misclassified Examples")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

show_misclassified(X_val, y_val, cnn_labels, "Vanilla CNN")
show_misclassified(X_val, y_val, vgg_labels, "VGG16")

Vanilla CNN - Total Misclassified: 223

VGG16 - Total Misclassified: 36

Conclusion

Based on the evaluation metrics, the VGG16 model significantly outperforms the Vanilla CNN in classifying images of cats and dogs.

Performance Summary:

  • Vanilla CNN

    • Accuracy: 75.8%
    • Precision & Recall: Balanced but moderate (Cat: 0.75/0.77, Dog: 0.77/0.74)
    • F1-score: ~0.76 for both classes
    • Confusion Matrix shows 113 false positives and 129 false negatives

  • VGG16

    • Accuracy: 95.8%
    • Precision & Recall: Very high (Cat: 0.97/0.95, Dog: 0.95/0.97)
    • F1-score: ~0.96 for both classes
    • Confusion Matrix shows only 42 total misclassifications

Insights:

  • The Vanilla CNN struggles with generalization, likely due to limited depth and lack of pre-trained features.
  • VGG16, leveraging transfer learning from ImageNet, demonstrates strong feature extraction and robustness.
  • Misclassified examples in CNN often involve ambiguous or low-quality images, while VGG16 handles these better.

Recommendation:

For practical deployment or further development, VGG16 is the preferred model due to its superior accuracy, precision, and reliability. The Vanilla CNN could be improved with techniques like data augmentation, deeper architecture, or more training data.
